I'll start by executing the file_operations_reader tool to read the input data, using the default path "data/input.json".

<tool_call>file_operations_reader
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            I'll execute the data_processing_validator tool to validate the data we read in the previous step, using default schema validation.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "data": {},
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "*": {
        "type": "any"
      }
    }
  },
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll execute the data_processing_transformer tool to transform our validated data, using JSON as both input and output format.

<tool_call>data_processing_transformer
{
  "input_format": "json",
  "output_format": "json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll use the file_operations_converter tool to convert our JSON data to XML format before transformation.

<tool_call>file_operations_converter
{
  "input_format": "json",
  "output_format": "xml", 
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll try an alternative approach by using the data_processing_transformer again, but this time with a different configuration that might handle JSON input better.

<tool_call>data_processing_transformer
{
  "input_format": "json",
  "output_format": "json",
  "options": {
    "force_json_input": true,
    "skip_validation": true
  }
}
</tool_call>

            I'll try a different approach by first parsing the data before transformation. I'll use the data_processing_parser tool to ensure the data is properly structured.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {
    "format": "json"
  }
}
</tool_call>
